thread.title: Cape volleyball shrugs off slow start, defeats Tech 3-0
thread.title_full: Cape volleyball shrugs off slow start, defeats Tech 3-0

author: newsroom@capegazette.com (Dan Cook)
title: Cape volleyball shrugs off slow start, defeats Tech 3-0
text:
Cape volleyball shrugs off slow start, defeats Tech 3-0 Vikings improve to 6-1 on season By Dan Cook | Oct 05, 2015 Photo by: Dan Cook Abby E'Nama roofs a block back into Tech's Kaylee Banning during the Lady Vikings' 3-0 victory over the Ravens. 
The Cape Henlopen volleyball team started off in slow motion Oct. 1 against a scrappy Sussex Tech squad but outlasted the Ravens 25-20, 25-22 and 25-11 to move to 6-1 on the season. 
"Sussex Tech was much more physical at the net than we expected," said Cape head coach Tyler Coupe. "We've been practicing quite a bit on spike coverage, [but] for some reason we weren't putting it into practice in the match. I told them that we can't rush it. We need to be smart and use the block to our advantage." 
"I think we need to carry over techniques we learn in practice," said senior Captain Izzie Marsico. "We will become a much stronger team if we play how we practice." 
The Vikings served 15 aces in the contest to Tech's three with Logan Shuttleworth picking up eight for the Lady Vikings. 
"Our serving was inconsistent during the first two sets. We gave them some free points in those sets," said Coupe. "They are a strong team, and you can't give a strong team free points." 
Logan Shuttleworth tallied 20 assists in the contest. 
"The more times Logan gets on the court, she's getting better and better," said Coupe. 
Alison Palmer, Marsico, Abbey E'Nama, Cameron Wick, Taylor Collier and Shuttleworth teamed for 24 kills in the match. 
Kira Vitella made eight digs for the libero position while Brittany Duvall added seven. Palmer, Shuttleworth, E'Nama, Marsico and Collier all had a good defensive match. 
Both teams wore something pink to support Breast Cancer Awareness Month. 
The junior varsity squad fell to the Ravens JV 0-2, moving their record to 4-2 on the season. 
Cape travels to Red Lion Tuesday, Oct. 6, for a matchup with the Lions. Cape coach Tyler Coupe gets pumped up for a Vikings play.
